es in any position, we obtain the array [10] at the end which is a palindrome.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n1 <= nums[i] <= 106\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        left = 0\n        right = len(nums) - 1\n        operations = 0\n        \n        while left < right:\n            if nums[left] == nums[right]:\n                left += 1\n                right -= 1\n            elif nums[left] < nums[right]:\n                nums[left + 1] += nums[left]\n                left += 1\n                operations += 1\n            else:\n                nums[right - 1] += nums[right]\n                right -= 1\n                operations += 1\n        \n        return operations\n```\n\nThis solution uses a two-pointer approach to try and make the array a palindrome with the minimum number of operations. The pointers start at the beginning and the end of the array, and the algorithm either merges the left element with the next one or the right element with the previous one, depending on which is smaller, until the two pointers meet or cross each other. This ensures that the number of operations is minimized.", "estimated_date": 1664064000000}